not asthma or ailment, but just living a normal life. Most people expect all Indians, irrespective of age, are incapable of doing a job. I can do a 8-hour day easily, and opt to work for 6 hours a day. Yet the office gives me loads of work. No matter what is without physical strain, I am asked to do it. My 80 year old mother gets good treatment because people can see she is suffering and disabled.

Posted by: na | August 8, 2007 1:29 AM

And we wonder why we have a shortage of doctors in America

Michael DeBakey, in the pharmaceutical section of the local WalMart. The pharmacist told me to enter through the pharmaceutical dept door because it's harder for me to bend as it previously used to. Gasp.

My fiancee a physician who has to wear a wrist device that counts her EVERY finger motion; Palm Pilots with internet printing have put Amazing sighs of relief in the unused eyes of "Medical Axons"....

I hate walking, standing!

There was a Tweetmeister on NPR this morning, asking, "Why is it no one has invented a sit-to stand computer, where you can sit and then adjust to standing?" Why should you have to get up and download and then sit down again?
